

Important enterprise rule
Storage design should consider:
•	IOPS
•	throughput
•	backup strategy
•	disaster recovery
•	scaling
Size alone is not the main factor.
When planning large storage (like 10 TB or more) in OpenShift Container Platform / Kubernetes, enterprise architects evaluate several storage design factors before creating the PVC. The most important ones are IOPS, throughput, access mode, backup strategy, and future growth. Let’s go through them in depth.
________________________________________
1️⃣ IOPS (Input/Output Operations Per Second)
IOPS measures how many read/write operations the storage system can perform per second.
Example operations:
•	Reading a file block
•	Writing database records
•	Updating logs
Example
Application needs: 5000 IOPS
Storage volume provides: 500 IOPS
Result:
•	Slow database queries
•	Application latency
•	Pod performance degradation
Why it matters for large PVCs
Many people assume:
Large PVC size = High performance
But that is not always true.
Example:
Volume	Size	IOPS
Volume A	10 TB	3000 IOPS
Volume B	1 TB	6000 IOPS
Volume B can be faster even though it is smaller.
Enterprise practice
For heavy workloads (databases, analytics):
•	Use high-performance storage classes
•	Use multiple volumes for parallel I/O
Example:
App
 ├ PVC-1 → 3000 IOPS
 ├ PVC-2 → 3000 IOPS
 └ PVC-3 → 3000 IOPS
Total performance improves.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Throughput (Data Transfer Speed)
Throughput measures how much data can be transferred per second.
Common units:
•	MB/s
•	GB/s
Example:
Volume throughput: 250 MB/s
Application load: 800 MB/s
Result:
•	Data processing slows down
•	Storage queue builds up
Example workloads requiring high throughput
•	Video processing
•	Machine learning datasets
•	Data analytics pipelines
•	Large backups
Enterprise optimization
Teams sometimes distribute storage across multiple volumes:
10 TB dataset
 ├ 2 TB PVC
 ├ 2 TB PVC
 ├ 2 TB PVC
 ├ 2 TB PVC
 └ 2 TB PVC
Each volume contributes throughput.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Access Modes (RWO vs RWX)
In Kubernetes, PVCs have access modes that define how pods can use them.
ReadWriteOnce (RWO)
One node can mount the volume with read/write access.
Example:
Pod → PVC → Node1
If the pod moves to another node, the volume must detach and reattach.
Used for:
•	Databases
•	Stateful applications
________________________________________
ReadWriteMany (RWX)
Multiple nodes can mount the same volume simultaneously.
Example:
Pod-A (Node1)
Pod-B (Node2)
Pod-C (Node3)
     ↓
      Shared PVC
Used for:
•	Shared file systems
•	Application assets
•	ML models
•	Web servers
Backends supporting RWX include:
•	Ceph filesystem
•	Red Hat OpenShift Data Foundation
•	NFS storage
________________________________________
Why access mode matters
If you choose RWO but need multiple pods, the application will fail.
Example error:
Multi-attach error for volume
________________________________________
4️⃣ Backup Strategy
Backing up large PVCs (10 TB+) is challenging.
Backup concerns
Large volumes cause:
•	Long backup windows
•	Slow restores
•	Storage costs
Example:
PVC size: 10 TB
Backup speed: 200 MB/s
Backup time: ~14 hours
Enterprise strategies
Snapshot backups
Storage-level snapshots capture data quickly.
Supported by:
•	Ceph
•	cloud block storage
Example workflow:
PVC → Volume Snapshot → Backup storage
________________________________________
Incremental backups
Only changed data is backed up.
Benefits:
•	Faster backups
•	Reduced network load
________________________________________
Sharded backups
Instead of backing up one large PVC:
5 PVC × 2 TB
Backups can run in parallel.
________________________________________
5️⃣ Future Growth
Storage requirements almost always grow.
Example growth pattern:
Year 1 → 10 TB
Year 2 → 20 TB
Year 3 → 50 TB
If the architecture doesn't allow scaling, migrations become painful.
Enterprise planning
Architects design systems that can scale easily:
Example:
Initial storage
 ├ pvc-1 2TB
 ├ pvc-2 2TB
 └ pvc-3 2TB

Later expansion
 ├ pvc-4 2TB
 ├ pvc-5 2TB
No downtime required.
________________________________________
6️⃣ Storage Backend Consideration
The backend storage system also determines performance.
Common enterprise storage in OpenShift Container Platform clusters:
Storage	Use case
Red Hat OpenShift Data Foundation	Distributed enterprise storage
Ceph	Scalable block and file storage
Cloud block storage	Simple persistent volumes
Distributed storage platforms allow very large volumes with high availability.
________________________________________
7️⃣ Failure Domain Planning
With one large PVC:
Failure impact → entire 10 TB workload
With multiple volumes:
Failure impact → only one portion
This improves resilience.
________________________________________
⭐ Enterprise Decision Model
Architects typically evaluate storage with this checklist:
Factor	Key Question
IOPS	Can storage handle application operations?
Throughput	Can it move large datasets quickly?
Access Mode	Do multiple pods need access?
Backup	Can data be restored quickly?
Growth	Can storage scale easily?
________________________________________
✅ Typical enterprise recommendation for a 10 TB workload
If application supports distributed storage:
5 PVC × 2 TB
If application requires single filesystem:
1 PVC × 10 TB
But ensure high-performance storage class.
