List which Pods are using PVCs (very useful)
oc get pods -n <namespace> -o jsonpath='{range .items[*]}{.metadata.name}{"\t"}{range .spec.volumes[*]}{.persistentVolumeClaim.claimName}{" "}{end}{"\n"}{end}'
This helps identify which pod is consuming which PVC.

If you want PVC + StorageClass + Size in one table
oc get pvc -n <namespace> -o custom-columns=NAME:.metadata.name,STATUS:.status.phase,STORAGE:.spec.resources.requests.storage,STORAGECLASS:.spec.storageClassName
Pod → PVC mapping (most commonly used)
oc get pods -n <namespace> -o jsonpath='{range .items[*]}{.metadata.name}{"\t"}{range .spec.volumes[*]}{.persistentVolumeClaim.claimName}{" "}{end}{"\n"}{end}'
Example output:
pod-a    data-pvc logs-pvc
pod-b    cache-pvc
pod-c
Meaning:
•	pod-a uses data-pvc and logs-pvc
•	pod-b uses cache-pvc
•	pod-c does not use PVC
________________________________________
2️⃣ Cleaner formatted output (recommended)
oc get pods -n <namespace> -o json | jq -r '
.items[] |
.metadata.name as $pod |
.spec.volumes[]? |
select(.persistentVolumeClaim) |
"\($pod)\t\(.persistentVolumeClaim.claimName)"
'
Output:
pod-a    data-pvc
pod-a    logs-pvc
pod-b    cache-pvc
________________________________________
3️⃣ PVC → Pod mapping (useful for audits)
This shows which pods use each PVC.
for pvc in $(oc get pvc -n <namespace> -o jsonpath='{.items[*].metadata.name}'); do
  echo "PVC: $pvc"
  oc get pods -n <namespace> -o json | jq -r --arg pvc "$pvc" '
  .items[] |
  select(.spec.volumes[]?.persistentVolumeClaim.claimName==$pvc) |
  .metadata.name'
done
________________________________________
4️⃣ Find unused PVCs in a namespace (very useful cleanup check)
oc get pvc -n <namespace> -o json | jq -r '.items[].metadata.name' | while read pvc; do
  used=$(oc get pods -n <namespace> -o json | jq -r --arg pvc "$pvc" '
  .items[] |
  select(.spec.volumes[]?.persistentVolumeClaim.claimName==$pvc) |
  .metadata.name')
  
  if [ -z "$used" ]; then
    echo "Unused PVC: $pvc"
  fi
done
