In OpenShift Container Platform 4.16 and later, there is no universal “default = true” for allowVolumeExpansion at the platform level. It depends on the StorageClass, but most default CSI StorageClasses installed by OCP have it enabled (true). 
Default behavior in OCP 4.16+
•	OCP installs CSI-based StorageClasses by default.
•	These commonly show:
oc get storageclass
Example output:
NAME                    PROVISIONER           ALLOWVOLUMEEXPANSION
managed-csi (default)   disk.csi.azure.com    true
azurefile-csi           file.csi.azure.com    true
So in most OCP 4.16+ clusters, the default StorageClass already has:
allowVolumeExpansion: true
This means:
•	You can increase PVC size later
•	No data loss
•	Just edit the PVC size. 
________________________________________
How to confirm in your cluster (best practice)
Run:
oc get storageclass
Then:
oc describe storageclass <storageclass-name>
Look for:
AllowVolumeExpansion: True
________________________________________
Example real cluster check
oc get sc
Output:
NAME               PROVISIONER               RECLAIMPOLICY  ALLOWVOLUMEEXPANSION
ocs-storage-rbd    rbd.csi.ceph.com          Delete         true
gp3 (default)      ebs.csi.aws.com           Delete         true
Here PVC expansion is supported.


@@@@@@@@@@@@@2

In OCP 4.16 onward, most default CSI StorageClasses already have allowVolumeExpansion: true, so you can safely increase PVC size (e.g., 2Gi → 4Gi) without data loss

Why shrinking PVC is not supported
Kubernetes only supports volume expansion, not shrinking.
This restriction exists because:
•	Shrinking a filesystem can corrupt existing data.
•	The underlying storage systems (block storage, Ceph, EBS, etc.) often cannot safely reduce block size while data exists.
•	Kubernetes design intentionally blocks reducing .spec.resources.requests.storage.

